What makes a team to win the game in the English Premiere League?¶

Ruijie Ren

Introduction¶

As one of the biggest football leagues in the world, the English Premiere League has always been a joy to watch and every game there would be thousands of fans to be in the stadium and tens of thousands of people watching the game online. From the perspective of a football fan I would always appreciate every player's efforts and those brilliant goals and I would carefully read the game and think about the formation and the tactics, which makes me wondering, what makes a team to win a game in the premiere league?

If you are new to football, then feel free to check out the links below, which give detailed explanation of what happens on the pitch and how the two teams play the game back and forth. In short, there are so many formations and tactics that could be applied to the team and in order to beat our opponent, we have to find out the best solution. People always say that in football the tactics are evolving "spirally", which means there is no strictly dominant strategy in this game. If a team is full of skillful players then it might seem easy for them to take the winning but a relatively less powerful team might give up their possesion of the ball and try counter-attack to win the game.

Interestingly, the English Premiere League was not regarded as a league that could play "beautiful football" as La Liga (the Spanish football league) and in the season of 16-17 a Spanish manager Pep Guardiola arrived at the the Premiere League and began to coach one of the biggest team - Manchester City. He was the one who made the world realize the importance of possession and his team would always keep the ball in their side. Being curious of if Pep Guardiola indeed changed the league, I am going to collect the match data from the Premiere League and try to find the key factors for a team to win the game.

Further Readings¶

*A review of the 18-19 season: Premier League 2018-19 review: what we learned tactically from the season.

*A website that analyzes every team's tactics: PREMIER LEAGUE TACTICS.

*A tactic review of the 18-19 season: Premier League tactics 2018/19 review: 4-4-2 returns, the power of full-backs and every team assessed.

*A match analysis website: https://totalfootballanalysis.com/.

The above table is a standard match stat table of the data. I will use the data from the season 12-13 until now because in the earlier seasons the recordings of "possession" are all missing, which will play an important role in our analysis. The tables have many columns and I will pick the most relevant ones to the game:

  • timestamp: a timestamp that indicates the match time.
  • date_GMT: the kick-off time in Greenwich Mean Time.
  • status: a status indicating whether the game is complete or not.
  • home_team_name: the name of the home team.
  • away_team_name: the name of the away team.
  • home_team_goal_count: the goal scored by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_goal_count: the goal scored by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_corner_count: the corners kicked by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_corner_count: the corners kicked by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_yellow_cards: the number of yellow cards had by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_yellow_cards: the number of yellow cards had by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_red_cards: the number of red cards had by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_red_cards: the number of red cards had by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_shots: the number of shots by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_shots: the number of shots by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_shots_on_target: the number of shots on target by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_shots_on_target: the number of shots on target by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_fouls: the number of fouls by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_fouls: the number of fouls by the away team in the whole game.
  • home_team_possession: the possession percent by the home team in the whole game.
  • away_team_possession: the possession percent by the away team in the whole game.

Notice that even after we dropped the unplayed matches of the 19-20 season, there are still some rows that have the "-1" value. Since we are looking at the data of real world football game, the number of fouls can not be negative. It indicates that the piece of information is missing and it works the same as the "NaN" value, therefore we need to drop them.

However, in order to drop the rows that have the "-1" value, if we process the data one by one it would be exhausting and unefficient. Thus we need to define a function that does the job. At the same time, we want this function to concate the dataframes, since we have several seasons' data and it would be easy for us to manipulate the data if we can aggregate them in a single table.

Also, since the dataset does not have a column that indicates the result of the match, we have to add it manually. If you are not familiar with football, a winning team can have 3 points and the losing team get 0 point. If two teams are draw, then each team gets 1 point. Last, our function will also slice a single game to 2 rows, since one game (which is a single row) is played by 2 teams, this row actually provides 2 pieces of information of the match.

In [149]:
# our processing function, it takes a list of data (which is a list of seasons)
# and it combines the seasons into 1 single table
# it will clean the data by drop the rows that have value "-1"
# it also computes the result of every match and assign each team the points they get
# then it slice one single row to two rows since one game is played by
# two teams and it actually stores two pieces of information.
def process_data(list):
    # here we only take the necessary columns such as goals, shots...
    column_list = ['timestamp','date_GMT','home_team_name','away_team_name','home_team_goal_count','away_team_goal_count','home_team_corner_count','away_team_corner_count','home_team_yellow_cards','home_team_red_cards','away_team_yellow_cards','away_team_red_cards','home_team_shots','away_team_shots','home_team_shots_on_target','away_team_shots_on_target','home_team_fouls','away_team_fouls','home_team_possession','away_team_possession']
    # it combines the list of the data
    data = pd.concat(list)
    data = data[column_list]
    # we compute the result of the game and assign the point to the team
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] > data['away_team_goal_count'], 'home_team_point'] = 3
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] == data['away_team_goal_count'], 'home_team_point'] = 1
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] < data['away_team_goal_count'], 'home_team_point'] = 0
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] > data['away_team_goal_count'], 'away_team_point'] = 0
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] == data['away_team_goal_count'], 'away_team_point'] = 1
    data.loc[data['home_team_goal_count'] < data['away_team_goal_count'], 'away_team_point'] = 3
    # we slice one row to two rows
    home_team_list = ['timestamp','date_GMT','home_team_name','home_team_point','home_team_goal_count','home_team_corner_count','home_team_yellow_cards','home_team_red_cards','home_team_shots','home_team_shots_on_target','home_team_fouls','home_team_possession']
    away_team_list = ['timestamp','date_GMT','away_team_name','away_team_point','away_team_goal_count','away_team_corner_count','away_team_yellow_cards','away_team_red_cards','away_team_shots','away_team_shots_on_target','away_team_fouls','away_team_possession']
    home_team_data = data[home_team_list]
    away_team_data = data[away_team_list]
    # in order to join the two slices, we rename them
    home_team_data = home_team_data.rename(columns={"home_team_name": "team_name", "date_GMT":"season", "home_team_point": "point", "home_team_goal_count": "goal_count", "home_team_corner_count": "corner_count", "home_team_yellow_cards": "yellow_cards", "home_team_red_cards": "red_cards", "home_team_shots": "shots", "home_team_shots_on_target": "shots_on_target", "home_team_fouls": "fouls", "home_team_possession": "possession"})
    away_team_data = away_team_data.rename(columns={"away_team_name": "team_name", "date_GMT":"season", "away_team_point": "point", "away_team_goal_count": "goal_count", "away_team_corner_count": "corner_count", "away_team_yellow_cards": "yellow_cards", "away_team_red_cards": "red_cards", "away_team_shots": "shots", "away_team_shots_on_target": "shots_on_target", "away_team_fouls": "fouls", "away_team_possession": "possession"})
    data = pd.concat([home_team_data, away_team_data], axis=0)
    # here we also assign a catagorical data of "win/draw/lose"
    data.loc[data['point'] == 3, 'result'] = "win"
    data.loc[data['point'] == 1, 'result'] = "draw"
    data.loc[data['point'] == 0, 'result'] = "lose"
    # here we drop the rows that have the "-1" value
    index_to_remove = data[(data['corner_count'] == -1) | (data['yellow_cards'] == -1) | (data['red_cards'] == -1) | (data['shots'] == -1) | (data['shots_on_target'] == -1) | (data['fouls'] == -1) | (data['possession'] == -1)].index
    data.drop(index_to_remove , inplace=True)
    return data

Once the helper function is ready to use we can start to process our data by just calling it on a list.

The main table will be all the seasons available, which is from season1213 to season 1920 and the list will contain all the data files. We'll name it as "data".

Also, if you remember, at the introduction I mentioned that in the season of 16-17 a Spanish manager Pep Guardiola came to the Premier League and he is the one who shocked the world by his tactic of keeping ball possession. So we are also going to split the seasons by two parts, the first one is from 12-13 to 15-16, the second one is from 16-17 until now. They are called "old_data" and "new_data" respectively.

In [150]:
season_list = [season_1213,season_1314,season_1415,season_1516,season_1617,season_1718,season_1819,season_1920]
before_pep_list = [season_1213,season_1314,season_1415,season_1516]
after_pep_list = [season_1617,season_1718,season_1819,season_1920]
data = process_data(season_list)
old_data = process_data(before_pep_list)
new_data = process_data(after_pep_list)

Part IV: Regression¶

After exploring out the relations between the match stats, we can start to make our regression model. Since to win a game we need goals, and goals have high positive relation with shots and possession, then our model will be point = a shots + b possession + c

Part V: Conclusion¶

From our graphing and regression of the data, we see that to win a game, or, to get points, a team have to keep their possession of the ball, also they have to make more shots. Although it seems intuitive, the process that how we approach to this result also matters.
